TITLE: Book Review: ‘Triumph of the Yuppies,’ by Tom McGrath
SUMMARY: In “Triumph of the Yuppies,” Tom McGrath revels in the stories of a generation that turned its back on protest and bought into consumer culture.

TITLE: How Yu & Me, a Popular Chinatown Bookstore, Rebuilt After a Fire
SUMMARY: A fire left Lucy Yu’s literary hub in Chinatown gutted. She was determined to rebuild it.

TITLE: Want to Succeed as an Artist? We’ve Got a Coach For You.
SUMMARY: With a rising number of artists vying for a limited number of galleries and grants, arts professionals are pivoting to careers as coaches. But can they help people profit from their talents?

TITLE: TikTok Rediscovers Bag Balm, a Rural Beauty Secret
SUMMARY: Social media fans of Bag Balm, a moisturizer originally made for cows’ udders, say it’s just the thing for “slugging.”

TITLE: Ampla, a Lender to Consumer Brands, Faces Financial Struggles
SUMMARY: Ampla, which lent money to smaller businesses that sold clothing, home furnishings and other items directly to consumers, is struggling financially and seeking a buyer.

TITLE: Some Silicon Valley VCs Are Becoming More Conservative
SUMMARY: Marc Andreessen, Chamath Palihapitiya and several other tech venture capitalists are increasingly criticizing President Biden and making their disaffection known in an election year.

TITLE: The Paperless Post Founders Changed How We Party
SUMMARY: When James and Alexa Hirschfeld started Paperless Post 15 years ago, some saw its digital invitations as a fad. Instead, they have become a fixture of events and have spawned imitators.

TITLE: Chinese Firms Face Authoritarianism at Home and Hostility Abroad
SUMMARY: The experience of TikTok’s owner, ByteDance, in Beijing and Washington shows how much the ground has shifted for China’s entrepreneurs.

TITLE: A Cartier Program Is Helping Underrepresented Entrepreneurs
SUMMARY: The brand’s entrepreneurship program aims to expand opportunities for business owners creating “solutions for change.”

TITLE: Case Against Lodi, a Top NYC Restaurant, Could Lower Barriers to Unions
SUMMARY: The National Labor Relations Board says the management at Lodi unlawfully fought a union drive. If the allegations are upheld, the board could force the company to bargain.

TITLE: 6 Sumptuous European Hotels for Summer Travelers
SUMMARY: For Olympics-goers and just plain vacationers, here are new accommodations that offer a special taste of France, Italy and Greece.

TITLE: New Ho King, a Chinese Restaurant, Is Winning the Kendrick Lamar-Drake Beef
SUMMARY: New Ho King, open since 1976 in Toronto, has become an unlikely pop-culture battleground after being featured in songs from both rappers.

TITLE: Got an Idea for a Toy? Toymakers Want to Hear From You.
SUMMARY: Companies like Lego and Mattel have divisions that seek out design concepts directly from collectors and other highly dedicated fan bases.

TITLE: Sam Ash Music Stores to Close
SUMMARY: The chain, which started with a single shop in Brooklyn in 1924, said it would close all 42 of its locations by the end of July, citing competition from online retailers.

TITLE: The London Design Gallery at the Edge of Art and Design
SUMMARY: Carpenters Workshop Gallery has long pushed the limits of design. Now, they’ve made a bold bet on a new space in North Kensington. Will it pay off?

TITLE: Black Entrepreneurs, Frustrated by High Rates, Look to the Election
SUMMARY: In the battleground state of Georgia, some Black entrepreneurs are frustrated over the impact of higher interest rates, a source of economic anxiety.

TITLE: Even as He Faces Prison Time, Binance’s Founder Plans a Comeback
SUMMARY: Since pleading guilty to violating money-laundering rules, Changpeng Zhao, who ran the giant crypto exchange Binance, has networked across the United States to set up his next act.

TITLE: A Return to New York and, Finally, an Apartment She Can Afford
SUMMARY: After moving 10 times in 10 years, a woman found that a little luck was the best companion for a lot of hard work. She won a studio in a lottery on her fifth try.

TITLE: ‘To the Future’: Saudi Arabia Spends Big to Become an A.I. Superpower
SUMMARY: The oil-rich kingdom is plowing money into glitzy events, computing power and artificial intelligence research, putting it in the middle of an escalating U.S.-China struggle for technological influence.

TITLE: Binance Founder Should Get 3 Years in Prison, Prosecutors Say
SUMMARY: Lawyers for Changpeng Zhao, the founder of the crypto exchange Binance, countered that he should receive no prison time.
